  Treat each warning as suspect, not as something to silence. Before
  fixing, decide whether it points at a real bug:

    -Wsign-compare:   sometimes hides off-by-one or signed wrap. Look
                      at the actual range of values, not just the types.
                      If a count is genuinely size_t, change the loop
                      variable's type; only cast when the producer
                      really returns int.
    -Wpointer-sign:   the libopendkim API uses u_char* (DKIM byte data),
                      the daemon uses char* (printable strings). Most
                      warnings are at the boundary. Prefer narrow casts
                      at call sites over flipping API signatures
                      (touching dkim.h is high-blast-radius). If you do
                      change a signature, run the build to verify all
                      call sites compile.
    -Wunused-parameter: in callback stubs that must match a function
                      pointer signature, annotate with `(void) param;`
                      casts at the top of the body — that's the pattern
                      commit 56b5a27d already used. Don't change the
                      signature.
    -Wunused-but-set / -Wunused-variable: in test files (t-test*.c) the
                      set-but-unused write often documents a return
                      value that the test ignores. Safe to delete the
                      write OR add a `(void) var;` after the assignment
                      if it's load-bearing for readability. Prefer
                      delete.
    -Wignored-qualifiers: `const int foo()` is meaningless — drop the
                      qualifier on the prototype AND the definition.
    -Wunused-function: dkimf_checkfsnode — grep for callers across the
                      whole tree. If genuinely dead, delete it. If
                      behind an #ifdef that's currently off, wrap the
                      function in the same #ifdef.

  Workflow:
