Sonnet for most of it. The first 5 categories (-Wignored-qualifiers, -Wunused-variable, -Wunused-but-set-variable, -Wunused-function, -Wunused-parameter) are mechanical — (void) casts,
  deletions, qualifier removal. Sonnet handles that fine, faster and cheaper, and 130+ warnings means cost adds up.

  Switch to Opus for -Wsign-compare (113) and especially -Wpointer-sign (217). Those are where warnings can hide real bugs: a signed→unsigned compare that wraps, a u_char buffer passed to a
   function that mutates it as char, etc. The judgment "is this a type noise fix or am I papering over a bug?" is exactly where Opus's deeper reasoning pays off, and the API-vs-cast
  decision on -Wpointer-sign benefits from it too.
  
  Practically: start with /model sonnet, knock out categories 1–5, then /model opus for 6–7.
